07868nam a22010695i 9783110628609DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019944706  a97831106286097 a10.1515/97831106286092doi  a(DE-B1597)528687  a(OCoLC)1138547800  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB187.S6bH45 2020 7aPHI0020002bisacsh04a128/.122300aWorld Soul – Anima Mundi :bOn the Origins and Fortunes of a Fundamental Idea /ced. by Christoph Helmig. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VIII, 364 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTopics in Ancient Philosophy / Themen der antiken Philosophie ,x2198-3100 ;v800tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgment -- tContents -- tThe World Soul in Antiquity and beyond -- tPart I: Prehistory of the concept -- tIs the Logos a kind of World Soul? On the relationship between cosmology and psychology in Heraclitus -- tPart II: Plato’s Timaeus and Pseudo-Aristotle’s De Mundo -- tDisorderly motion and the World Soul in the Timaeus -- tDie „Seele“ des Seienden bei Platon: Sophistes 248e–249a und Timaios 30a–31c -- tAscoltare l’anima cosmica: riargomentazione ed esegesi tecnica κατὰ ζητήματα della divisio animae platonica -- tThe power of god in Pseudo-Aristotle’s De mundo: An alternative approach -- tPart III: Old Academy, Stoicism, and Middle Platonism -- tThe World Soul takes command: The doctrine of the World Soul in the Epinomis of Philip of Opus and in the academy of Polemon -- tApospasma: The World Soul and its individual parts in Stoicism -- tDie kosmische Seele bei Ps.-Timaios Lokros und den anderen Pseudopythagorica: kosmologische und erkenntnistheoretische Aspekte -- tCalcidius on Fate and the World Soul -- tPart IV: Neoplatonism -- tPlotinus on the World Soul -- tThe World Soul in the embryological theories of Porphyry and Plotinus -- tThe World Soul in Proclus’ Timaeus Commentary -- tFrom the particular soul to the World Soul: Some puzzles in Philoponus -- tPart V: Nachleben -- tWorld Soul and celestial heat. Platonic and Aristotelian ideas in the history of natural philosophy -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Ancient Citations -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Plato’s Timaeus onwards, the world or cosmos has been conceived of as a living, rational organism. Most notably in German Idealism, philosophers still talked of a ‘Weltseele’ (Schelling) or ‘Weltgeist’ (Hegel). This volume is the first collection of essays on the origin of the notion of the world soul (anima mundi) in Antiquity and beyond. It contains 14 original contributions by specialists in the field of ancient philosophy, the Platonic tradition and the history of theology. The topics range from the ‘obscure’ Presocratic Heraclitus, to Plato and his ancient readers in Middle and Neoplatonism (including the Stoics), to the reception of the idea of a world soul in the history of natural science. A general introduction highlights the fundamental steps in the development of the Platonic notion throughout late Antiquity and early Christian philosophy. Accessible to Classicists, historians of philosophy, theologians and invaluable to specialists in ancient philosophy, the book provides an overview of the fascinating discussions surrounding a conception that had a long-lasting effect on the history of Western thought.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 0aSoulxHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aBaltzly, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaluori, Damian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc